I had the pleasure of joining my bby for the holidays back home 🇸🇷, it was truly peaceful, beautiful and enlightening. Suriname is a small country on the northeastern coast of South America, strongly influenced by many cultures they’re focused on taking care of the soul, while eating natural foods from the island. This experience has been positively transformative, one of the many reasons I love to travel. 

While being there I learned a saying “𝘑𝘦 𝘩𝘦𝘣𝘵 𝘵𝘸𝘦𝘦 𝘰𝘳𝘦𝘯, 𝘮𝘢𝘢𝘳 𝘫𝘦 𝘩𝘰𝘰𝘳𝘵 𝘸𝘰𝘰𝘳𝘥𝘦𝘯 𝘯𝘰𝘰𝘪𝘵 𝘵𝘸𝘦𝘦 𝘬𝘦𝘦𝘳” although self-explanatory, I understood the importance of it especially in today’s society. We hardly listen to and understand each other, by doing so we can view life from an entirely new perspective, you learn more observe more; which in turn makes you a wiser and more mature person. Capable of conquering the universe’s hardest obstacles. 

This year was filled with ups and downs, you win some you lose some. I see every loss as a win because I’ve learned a lesson which only makes me greater. But no matter what life throws at me, I’m truly grateful for everything and everyone in my life. I wouldn’t change a thing. 

To new days, new blessings and new adventures. Happy New Years everyone🦋🧿

2 years and $30k later 🎓

Even though I graduated years ago during covid, it felt official walking across that stage. This one’s for my mom, I couldn’t do it without you (and Margaret my second mom lol). I’m so grateful, for them, and everyone and everything that’s guided me throughout this long and hard journey 🥹. "If it doesn't challenge you, it doesn't change you." I really couldn’t have done it without each and everyone who was there for me from the beginning, and I’ll never forget it. You’ve made me the woman I am today, and I’ve never been so proud and content with myself after these years of pain and suffering, mistakes and victories, and lots of lessons learned both in class and real life. “You miss 100% of the shots you don’t take”, so take it from me, follow your dreams, and aspire to inspire.

Also wanted to extend a special thanks those who were there for me, and those who couldn’t be there but gifted or helped finance my education or just made me feel like a princess (bc I really did feel like one👑). Huge s/o to my friend, who flew in and surprise me for my special day🥹, ily. I know I don’t act like it, but I didn’t expect anything from anyone. I didn’t even invite anyone to my graduation (esp because it was 2 years later lol). So thank you for going the extra mile supporting me, I love you all and am beyond grateful🦋

I love a good party, but #Independence, for who? 

Let’s not forget black people were still enslaved July 4, 1776.  Frederick Douglass, in 1852, was invited to address the citizens of New York. On the 76th anniversary of the signing of the Declaration of Independence, Douglass used the occasion not to celebrate the nation's triumphs but to remind all of its continuing enslavement of millions of people.
“Mr. President, Friends, and Fellow Citizens: He who could address this audience without a quailing sensation, has stronger nerves than I have. I do not remember ever to have appeared as a speaker before any assembly more shrinkingly, nor with greater distrust of my ability, than I do this day. A feeling has crept over me, quite unfavorable to the exercise of my limited powers of speech. This Fourth July is yours, not mine. You may rejoice, I must mourn. To drag a man in fetters into the grand illuminated temple of liberty, and call upon him to join you in joyous anthems, were inhuman mockery and sacrilegious irony. Fellow-citizens, above your national, tumultuous joy, I hear the mournful wail of millions! Whose chains, heavy and grievous yesterday, are, to-day, rendered more intolerable by the jubilee shouts that reach them. Standing there identified with the American bondman, making his wrongs mine, I do not hesitate to declare, with all my soul, that the character and conduct of this nation never looked blacker to me than on this 4th of July! What, to the American slave, is your 4th of July? I answer; a day that reveals to him, more than all other days in the year, the gross injustice and cruelty to which he is the constant victim.” 

The great Frederick Douglass delivered this speech as 171 years ago, and though slavery is no longer the law of this land, his overall sentiments about the lack of rights and freedoms for Black America still ring true, especially in light of last week's disappointing and dangerous Supreme Court decisions. Let's keep fighting for a freer nation✊🏽

Thanks to blackpast.org , @naturbanleague , @blackhistoryunlocked for all the information. #independenceday #1776 #blm #blackindependence
